title: For Sale:  Gold plated Winchester commemorative rifle
postcontent: Burlington / Elon area. I will meet near Greensboro.Rifle is in the box and as new as the day it was built, in 1980. Still wrapped in the original wax lined paper that protects the rifle. All the manuals and paperwork are like new. Rifle was manufactured in the year of 1980 only, it is a numbered and limited run, and is the "Oliver Winchester" gold plated and engraved commemorative lever action rifle.  It is engraved everywhere on both sides of the gold plated receiver. It has a gold plated lever, as well as a gold plated foreend cap. It has the octagon barrel with gold engraved "Oliver Winchester" signature enlayed on the side of the barrel. Also has the Oliver Winchester medallon embedded in the side of the butt stock. There were 19,999 of these made. This one is in the 3000's(serial number).I've got many clear and crisp pics, from every angle, that I can send if you are serious and sitting on $850 cash.This thing is stunning; the gold, the engraving, the wood, the checkering in the wood, all of it is on a level that I have not seen anywhere, since acquiring this rifle. You cannot see that in the one picture included with this listing.Rifle is in 38-55 caliber, which is consistent with a 38special in diameter, but the casing (and its powder content) is longer than even a 30-30 round.This caliber was the "go-to" caliber before the 30-30 from Winchester took its place. I will give you a collector's box of ammo to go with it  It is not overly expensive ammunition nor is it hard to find, in case you this rifle as a shooter and need ammo. I myself had never heard of the 38-55 caliber, but later learned that this is the caliber that all of America was using, back when Americans were primarily horseback with a lever rifle in their scabbard.Exceptional rifle in every way, recouping some of the expense of Christmas.Price is firm as granite. No trades, just looking for cash.

title: For Sale:  Pre-Production S&W .357 581
postcontent: Bought this a few years ago with bad timing. Fixed the timing on it recently and decided to thin the herd a little. I dont shoot it and do not keep to keep it. I am more into semi-auto pistols, and currently have a few too many. Pistol will come with a couple boxes of .357 magnum ammo and if I have any .38 ammo that will go with it too.These were only made for a couple years in the early 80s (81-84 I believe). Mine is one of the earliest 581s made, it is said to be a pre-production model due to the serial number. Serial number starts with AAA which dates to 1980, they didnt come out until 1981. With it being so early I have thought about getting the Factory Letter from S&W but right now I am too cheap to spend $50 to get it done.Blueing is nice, but NOT perfect. It does have some holster wear on the end of the barrel, and it has been shot quite a bit. I do not have the original wood grips, the grips I have on it are a set of Pachmyer presentation grips. Looking to sell, Not looking for trades. I don't NEED to sell so do not lowball me. This is a cool piece of history and have been told by several S&W enthusiests that it could be worth $800+ because of how early it is. I do not know if its worth $800, I have seen them sell on Gunbroker for around what I am asking. Looking to get $650 I would to open to reasonable offers. DO NOT lowball me, I will not give it away.
